<TITLE> Moneysupermarket says 2008 on track, Money lags </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, April 22 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Price comparison website Moneysupermarket.com's revenues grew 30 percent in the first quarter of 2008, but its Money division was a relative laggard due to the credit crunch, managing growth of just over 10 percent. Fewer people are using the UK's largest price comparison site to apply for loans and mortgages than a year ago, and trading in that area has been "challenging", the company said in Tuesday's trading update. Applications for credit cards and savings accounts, also part of the Money division, which makes up around half of revenue, have seen significant growth because of better terms being offered by banks and because an extra 15 percent of viewers have visited the Money section of the website. Revenue from the Insurance division, which makes up over a third of revenues, grew 50 percent in the first quarter. "As the group enters the second quarter, growth rates continue to remain strong and the current financial year continues to progress in line with the board's expectations," Moneysupermarket.com said in a statement. Shares in Moneysupermarket.com have struggled since floating at 170p/share last July in the biggest internet IPO since Google . The shares have lost 40 percent of their value since then, and 8 percent in the last week alone ahead of Tuesday's update, because of concerns about the slowdown in mortgages and loans busine
